Governor Rotimi Akeredolu of Ondo State has tested positive for COVID-19, the coronavirus disease that has infected 10 million people around the world and led TO 500,000 deaths. The governor made the announcement on Tuesday in a tweet he posted . The governor is currently self-isolating and under supervised home management by a team from the state’s Infectious Disease Hospital. The tweet read, “Today, I tested positive for #COVID19. All is well. I’m asymptomatic and have been self -isolating. Work continues. Your continued prayers over my wellbeing are most appreciated.” Ondo State presently has 276 confirmed cases of COVID-19. On Monday, the Nigeria Centre for Disease Control (NCDC) reported 32 new cases of the disease in the state. The Nigeria Centre for Disease Control (NCDC) has reported 566 new cases of COVID-19 infections in Nigeria taking the country’s confirmed cases to 25,133. The NCDC on Monday also reported the death toll from the coronavirus disease as 573 and put the number of recoveries as 9,493. Lagos State recorded the highest number of new cases with 166. It was followed by Oyo State which had 66 cases. Delta State recorded 53 new cases while Ebonyi State had 43. In Plateau State, there were 34 news cases, 32 in Ondo State, 26 in the Federal Capital Territory (FCT) and 25 in Ogun State. Edo State had 24 new cases, 15 in Imo State , 13 in Bayelsa State, 12 in Benue State, 11 each in Gombe, Kano and Kaduna states, eight on Osun State, seven in Nasarawa State, five in Borno and two each in Katsina and Anambra states.